Package jtuple

Class Tuple

java.lang.Object
jtuple.Tuple
All Implemented Interfaces:
java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Comparable<java.lang.Object>, java.lang.Iterable<java.lang.Object>
public class Tuple
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Iterable<java.lang.Object>, java.lang.Comparable<java.lang.Object>
Represents a generic tuple of objects. The behavior of this structure allows to write simple code, while aggregating objects in a single immutable structure.
A tuple is a statically sized structure, whose elements cannot be removed, added neither replaced after its construction.
A tuple object is serializable, iterable and lexicographically comparable to any other tuple object.
A tuple object is perfectly suitable for using it as a key for hash maps and sorted maps.

The get(int) method allows to get the object at the given index in the tuple, casting it automatically to the destination type.

The toArray() and the toArray(Class) methods allow to get an array, of objects or of the specified type, respectively, containing the values of the tuple. These methods can be used to pass the tuple values as varargs to methods (e.g., to the PrintStream.printf(String, Object...) method). This class implements persistence (i.e., modifier operations generate new tuples, rather than modifying the current one).

    • isEmpty

      public boolean isEmpty()
      Gets the "empty" status of this values.
      A values is "empty" (i.e. it is a "null values") if it has no elements, i.e. its length is 0.
      An empty values is a normal values and it is part of the set of all possible tuples, such as the 0 number is a normal number respect to the set of Natural Numbers.
      Returns:
      true if the values has no element, false otherwise
